 2 emissions, are expected to constrain the survival and reproduction of many marine organisms (
 
  1
 ). Existing knowledge implies that physiological limits of early life history stages define the vulnerability of species to OWA (
 
  2
 ). Studies of worst-case impact scenarios are important to raise risk awareness and gain societal acceptance for mitigation policy (
 
  3
 ). However, even more important is the identification of emission pathways required to minimize impact risks and to locate potential refuge habitats of endangered species that should receive priority in conservation (
 
